english:
  title: A Royal Inquiry
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King speaks thus: I am but faint in virtue and limited in wisdom, yet I bear the accumulated grace of my ancestors and embrace the trust of my officials and people who have elevated me to the throne. The burden is great and the responsibility heavy—I know not how to proceed, and truly I tremble with fear. Looking back to the examples of former rulers, I seek to establish a realm of modest harmony. Consulting the Book of Documents, I find: "King Wen labored from dawn through midday without respite for food, thereby bringing peace to all the people." Yet it also says: "King Wen regarded matters of speech and justice as though nothing required his attention." What then does it mean that he had no leisure? Since ancient times, those who rule the realm prosper through diligence and decline through indolence. Yet to know only that one must be diligent, without understanding how to be diligent, brings its own ruin—a severity that becomes oppressive and offers no aid to true governance.

    What then should occupy the diligence of a ruler? Each time I hold audience to hear reports, I fear lest even one matter fall into neglect. Yet the Ten Thousand Matters press upon me in abundance—how can I discern what is fitting and act without error? I inquire and investigate ceaselessly, fearing that the sentiments of the people below remain unheard—how can I broaden my perception so that nothing remains hidden from view? When I issue edicts, I worry lest they meet resistance and fail to take root—how can I ensure they align with what is right, so that the people willingly submit?

    You gentlemen are learned in the Classics and versed in both ancient and modern affairs. Surely you possess insight into these matters. Speak with full attention, neither hastily nor carelessly. I shall consider your words carefully and put them into practice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This work is a royal examination prompt (책제) in which King Taejo of Joseon poses philosophical questions about wise governance to his scholars, drawing on Confucian ideals and precedents from ancient Chinese kings.
  - key: ''
    value: The apparent paradox between King Wen's constant labor and his effortless governance reflects the Confucian ideal that virtuous rulership operates through moral influence rather than excessive personal intervention.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Ten Thousand Matters' (萬機) is a traditional metaphor for the comprehensive responsibilities of imperial administration.
